  <h2 id="methodology">Our Methodology in Plain Language</h2>
  <p>We know "algorithmic cycle prediction" can sound like it's hiding something. It isn't. Here is exactly what we do:</p>
  <ol style="margin:0 0 16px 20px;color:var(--muted2);font-size:0.88rem;">
    <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Identify the anchor:</strong> Find the definitive structural low of the previous bear market (the date when selling pressure was structurally exhausted — confirmed by a major capitulation event like the FTX collapse).</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Add 1,064 days:</strong> The predicted ATH date.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Add 364 days to the ATH:</strong> The predicted next ATL date.</li>
    <li style="margin-bottom:10px;"><strong style="color:var(--text);">Repeat recursively:</strong> Each new ATL becomes the anchor for the next cycle. No additional inputs required.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>That's it. The entire model. Anyone with a calendar and basic arithmetic can verify every number on this site.</p>
  <p>We do <strong>not</strong> incorporate price targets, on-chain metrics, sentiment analysis, macroeconomic variables, or halving dates into the model. Those are valuable analytical tools — but they are separate tools. The 1064/364 model is purely temporal.</p>

